%%TITLE
Ki67 Expression has Prognostic Significance in Relation to Human Papillomavirus Status in Oropharyngeal Squamous Cell Carcinoma.
%%ABSTRACT
Human papillomavirus (HPV) is the major predictor of outcome in oropharyngeal squamous cell carcinoma (OSCC) but the disease is heterogeneous and there is limited understanding of the prognostic significance of other molecular markers in relation to HPV. This multi-institutional, retrospective study examined the prognostic significance of Ki67 expression in association with HPV status in OSCC.The 105 patients recruited had a median follow-up of 70 months. Tumor HPV status was determined by HPV E6-targeted multiplex real-time polymerase chain reaction/p16 semiquantitative immunohistochemistry and Ki67 expression by semiquantitative immunohistochemistry. Determinants of recurrence and mortality hazards were modelled using Cox regression with censoring at dates of last follow-up.HPV and Ki67 positivity rates were 46 and 44 %, respectively. HPV-positive cancers were more likely to be Ki67-positive. On multivariate analysis, both HPV and Ki67 were predictors of outcome. Ki67-positive cancers were associated with a 3.13-fold increased risk of disease-related death compared with Ki67-negative cancers. Among HPV-negative patients, Ki67-positive disease was associated with 5.6-fold increased risk of oropharyngeal cancer-related death (p = 0.002), 5.5-fold increased risk of death from any cause (p = 0.001), and 2.9-fold increased risk of any event (p = 0.013). The risk of locoregional failure was lowest in patients with HPV-positive/Ki67-positive cancers.Ki67 predicts disease-related death in oropharyngeal cancer independent of HPV status. A combination of Ki67 and HPV status provides improved prognostic information relative to HPV status alone. Our data suggest, for the first time, that Ki67 status has prognostic value, particularly in HPV-negative oropharyngeal cancer.
%%MATERIALS AND METHODS
Study Population
The study group comprised 105 patients with OSCC treated with curative intent at seven Australian hospitals between 1982 and 2008. The study was approved by the Ethics Committees of Sydney South West Area Health Service (Protocols X05-0208, CH62/6/2006-041, 2006/ 055). Demographic and clinicopathological data were obtained from the institutional databases and patient records. Selection criteria included availability of primary tumor for Ki67 immunostaining, and availability of base- line clinicopathological data and follow-up data. Follow-up status was confirmed by treating or primary physicians. Patients were followed up for the occurrence of an event, defined as recurrence in any form or death from any cause, for a median of 70 months after diagnosis. The study pathologist reviewed the histology and tumor grade in all cases, and cancers were staged using the 7th edition of the American Joint Committee on Cancer staging system.
Laboratory Studies
Ki67 expression was examined by immunohistochemis- try. Sections (4 lm thick) were cut from each paraffin block and deparaffinized. Antigen retrieval was performed by microwaving for 10 min, during which sections were placed in a modified citrate target retrieval buffer pH 6.1 (Dako, Melbourne, VIC, Australia). The slides were then cooled to room temperature by immersing in a running-water bath for
20 min, followed by washing in Tris-buffered saline with
% Tween-20 (TBST) for 5 min. The slides were pro- cessed in an autostainer (Dako) programmed with the following steps: (1) 2-min wash with Tris-buffered saline;
(2) peroxidase block with 3 % hydrogen peroxide for 5 min to quench endogenous peroxidase activity; (3) incubation with primary monoclonal rabbit Ki67 antibody (Abcam, Cambridge, UK) at a 1:200 dilution for 60 min, followed by two washes with TBST; (4) incubation with peroxidase- conjugated secondary antibody using EnVision? Dual Link System Peroxidase (Dako) for 30 min, followed by two
washes with TBST; (5) the slides were developed with 3,30- diamino-benzidine tetrahydrochloride (DAB) solution
(Dako) and counterstained with Harris hematoxylin. As a negative control, a separate set of slides was incubated in TBST buffer instead of the Ki67 rabbit primary antibody. All slides were finally dehydrated and mounted with DPX mountant (BDH Prolabo Chemicals, Australia) and imaged on the Olympus Provis photomicroscope and DP70 camera. Since there has been no consensus in the literature on Ki67 cut-offs in studies of oropharyngeal cancer,– we analyzed distribution in the percentage of cancer cells found to be Ki67-positive and found them to be clustered into two distinct groups: \50 and [50 %. Hence, positive staining was defined as nuclear staining in [50 % of the cancer cells (electronic supplementary Fig. 1). Scoring of the immunohistochemistry was performed by the study
pathologist, who was blinded to the clinical data.
Evidence that HPV is transcriptionally active is needed to establish oncogenicity in OSCCs. In previous studies, overexpression of p16 resulting from downregulation of the retinoblastoma protein by the HPV E7 oncoprotein has been used as a surrogate marker of HPV E7 expression., In the current study, an HPV-positive cancer was defined as one testing positive for HPV DNA and with p16ink(p16) overexpression on immunohistochemistry.,The presence and type of HPV DNA were determined by an E6-based multiplex tandem polymerase chain reaction assay (MT- PCR) carried out on two to six 5 lm sections of tumor using modifications of the tandem method of Stanley and Szewczuk, as previously described. This assay simul- taneously detects and identifies 21 HPV types (16, 18, 31,
33, 35, 39, 45, 51, 52, 56, 58, 59, 66, 68, 70, 73, 82, 53, 6,
11 and 26). Measured quantities of equine herpes virus were introduced during the extraction process and used to monitor the efficiency of DNA extraction and removal of PCR inhibitors. The expression of p16 was determined by semiquantitative immunohistochemistry using the JC2 p16 antibody (Neomarkers, Fremont, CA, USA), as previously described. Staining was typically strong and diffuse across the nucleus and cytoplasm of cancer cells, and
recorded as positive if staining was seen in more than 50 % of cancer cells.
Statistical Analyses
Comparisons between clinicopathological and demo- graphic characteristics of Ki67-positive and Ki67-negative cancers were undertaken using t-tests for continuous
variables and Chi-square tests for categorical variables. The Kaplan–Meier method was used to construct time-to- event curves. Times to locoregional failure, an event, death from oropharyngeal cancer, or death from any cause were calculated from the date of diagnosis. Locoregional failure was defined as clinical, radiological, and/or pathological evidence of recurrence at the primary site or in the regional nodal area. Patients were censored at last follow-up/death/

distant recurrence where applicable, or excluded if they had incomplete information on recurrence. For the analysis of time to death from any cause, patients were censored at last follow-up if they were alive. For the analysis of time to death with oropharyngeal cancer, patients were censored at last follow-up/death without oropharyngeal cancer where applicable; one patient was excluded as it was not known whether this patient died with or without OSCC. Univariate and multivariate time-to-event analyses were performed using Cox proportional hazards regression modelling. Statistical analyses were performed using SPSS software version 22 (IBM Corporation, Armonk, NY, USA).
